definition: "The urine albumin-to-creatinine ratio (ACR) measures the amount of albumin — a major blood protein — appearing in the urine, normalized to creatinine concentration to correct for urine dilution. Healthy kidneys retain albumin in the bloodstream; their filtration barrier (the glomerular basement membrane) is normally impermeable to albumin. When the glomerular barrier is damaged — by hypertension, hyperglycemia, inflammation, or other insults — albumin leaks through into the urine. Microalbuminuria refers to albumin excretion in the range of 30–300 mg/g creatinine — too small to detect on standard urinalysis dipstick (which only turns positive above ~150–300 mg/g), but measurable with specific immunoassay. Macroalbuminuria (or clinical proteinuria) is defined as ACR above 300 mg/g. Expressing albumin as a ratio to creatinine compensates for variation in urine concentration across specimens, allowing a random urine sample (rather than a 24-hour collection) to provide reliable quantitative information about albumin excretion rate."
why_it_matters: "The ACR is one of the most important and underutilized markers in longevity medicine. Its primary value is in detecting glomerular damage at a stage — microalbuminuria, ACR 30–300 mg/g — when the damage is often reversible with appropriate intervention. By the time serum creatinine rises or eGFR falls, substantial nephron loss has typically already occurred. The ACR detects kidney filtration barrier dysfunction years before these traditional kidney function markers show any change. Beyond kidney disease, microalbuminuria is an independent cardiovascular risk marker. Systematic reviews consistently find that even mildly elevated ACR (above 10 mg/g in the general population) is associated with meaningfully higher cardiovascular event rates and all-cause mortality, independent of diabetes, hypertension, and other conventional risk factors. The proposed mechanisms include endothelial dysfunction (the same vascular injury that causes glomerular leakage also damages systemic endothelium) and chronic low-grade inflammation — both of which are central to cardiovascular aging. This means the ACR is not just a kidney marker — it is a window into systemic vascular health."

standard_range: "Normal: < 30 mg/g (mg albumin per g creatinine) · Microalbuminuria: 30–300 mg/g · Macroalbuminuria: > 300 mg/g"
